.css-b3gji5{position:relative;z-index:1;}@media (min-width:0px) and (max-width:767.95px){.css-b3gji5{margin-block-end:var(--mobile-widget-gap, 16px);padding-block:var(--widget-extra-padding, 12px);}}@media (min-width:768px) and (max-width:1069.95px){.css-b3gji5{margin-block-end:var(--mobile-widget-gap, 16px);padding-block:var(--widget-extra-padding, 12px);}}@media (min-width:0px) and (max-width:767.95px){.css-b3gji5 .evaaos92{min-block-size:180px;}}@media (min-width:768px) and (max-width:1069.95px){.css-b3gji5 .evaaos92{min-block-size:270px;}}

Arrivals from the Americas and Europe, which account for a sizeable share of Nepal’s higher-spending long-haul tourism business, dropped by nearly 25 per cent and 19 per cent, respectively, during March compared with the same period last year, official figures show.

Even so, stronger demand from Asian markets helped limit the overall damage, with total visitor numbers slipping by just 1 per cent as the Iran war escalated last month.

